# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nc-class
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In computer science, **analysis of parallel algorithms** is the process of finding the computational complexity of algorithms executed in parallel – the amount of time, storage, or other resources needed to execute them.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In many respects, analysis of parallel algorithms is similar to the analysis of sequential algorithms, but is generally more involved because one must reason about the behavior of multiple cooperating threads of execution.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] One of the primary goals of parallel analysis is to understand how a parallel algorithm's use of resources (speed, space, etc.) changes as the number of processors is changed.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] A so-called work-time (WT) (sometimes called work-depth, or work-span) framework was originally introduced by Shiloach and Vishkin for conceptualizing and describing parallel algorithms.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] In the WT framework, a parallel algorithm is first described in terms of parallel rounds.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For each round, the operations to be performed are characterized, but several issues can be suppressed.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For example, the number of operations at each round need not be clear, processors need not be mentioned and any information that may help with the assignment of processors to jobs need not be accounted for.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Second, the suppressed information is provided.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The inclusion of the suppressed information is guided by the proof of a scheduling theorem due to Brent, which is explained later in this article.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The WT framework is useful since while it can greatly simplify the initial description of a parallel algorithm, inserting the details suppressed by that initial description is often not very difficult.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] For example, the WT framework was adopted as the basic presentation framework in the parallel algorithms books (for the parallel random-access machine PRAM model) and, as well as in the class notes .
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] The overview below explains how the WT framework can be used for analyzing more general parallel algorithms, even when their description is not available within the WT framework.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Suppose computations are executed on a machine that has p processors.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Let Tp denote the time that expires between the start of the computation and its end.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] Analysis of parallel algorithms is usually carried out under the assumption that an unbounded number of processors is available.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] This is unrealistic, but not a problem, since any computation that can run in parallel on N processors can be executed on *p* < *N* processors by letting each processor execute multiple units of work.
[src:nc-class/analysis-of-parallel-algorithms] showing that the span (depth) *T*∞ and the work *T*1 together provide reasonable bounds on the computation time.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] In computational complexity theory and circuit complexity, a **Boolean circuit** is a mathematical model for combinational digital logic circuits.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A formal language can be decided by a family of Boolean circuits, one circuit for each possible input length.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Boolean circuits are defined in terms of the logic gates they contain.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] For example, a circuit might contain binary AND and OR gates and unary NOT gates, or be entirely described by binary NAND gates.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Each gate corresponds to some Boolean function that takes a fixed number of bits as input and outputs a single bit.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Boolean circuits provide a model for many digital components used in computer engineering, including multiplexers, adders, and arithmetic logic units, but they exclude sequential logic.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] They are an abstraction that omits many aspects relevant to designing real digital logic circuits, such as metastability, fanout, glitches, power consumption, and propagation delay variability.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] In giving a formal definition of Boolean circuits, Vollmer starts by defining a basis as set *B* of Boolean functions, corresponding to the gates allowable in the circuit model.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A Boolean circuit over a basis *B*, with *n* inputs and *m* outputs, is then defined as a finite directed acyclic graph.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Each vertex corresponds to either a basis function or one of the inputs, and there is a set of exactly *m* nodes which are labeled as the outputs.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] The edges must also have some ordering, to distinguish between different arguments to the same Boolean function.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] As a special case, a propositional formula or Boolean expression is a Boolean circuit with a single output node in which every other node has fan-out of 1.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Thus, a Boolean circuit can be regarded as a generalization that allows shared subformulas and multiple outputs.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A common basis for Boolean circuits is the set {AND, OR, NOT}, which is functionally complete, i.e. from which all other Boolean functions can be constructed.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A particular circuit acts only on inputs of fixed size.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] However, formal languages (the string-based representations of decision problems) contain strings of different lengths, so languages cannot be fully captured by a single circuit (in contrast to the Turing machine model, in which a language is fully described by a single Turing machine).
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A language is instead represented by a *circuit family*.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A circuit family is an infinite list of circuits $(C_{0},C_{1},C_{2},...)$ , where $C_{n}$ has n input variables.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A circuit family is said to decide a language L if, for every string w , w is in the language L if and only if $C_{n}(w)=1$ , where n is the length of w .
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] In other words, a language is the set of strings which, when applied to the circuits corresponding to their lengths, evaluate to 1.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Several important complexity measures can be defined on Boolean circuits, including circuit depth, circuit size, and the number of alternations between AND gates and OR gates.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] For example, the size complexity of a Boolean circuit is the number of gates in the circuit.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] There is a natural connection between circuit size complexity and time complexity.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Intuitively, a language with small time complexity (that is, requires relatively few sequential operations on a Turing machine), also has a small circuit complexity (that is, requires relatively few Boolean operations).
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Formally, it can be shown that if a language is in ${\mathsf {TIME}}(t(n))$ , where t is a function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , then it has circuit size complexity $O(t^{2}(n))$ .
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Several important complexity classes are defined in terms of Boolean circuits.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] The most general of these is P/poly, the set of languages that are decidable by polynomial-size circuit families.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] It follows directly from the fact that languages in ${\mathsf {TIME}}(t(n))$ have circuit complexity $O(t^{2}(n))$ that P $\subseteq$ P/poly.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] In other words, any problem that can be computed in polynomial time by a deterministic Turing machine can also be computed by a polynomial-size circuit family.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] It is further the case that the inclusion is proper (i.e.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] P $\subsetneq$ P/poly) because there are undecidable problems that are in P/poly.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] P/poly turns out to have a number of properties that make it highly useful in the study of the relationships between complexity classes.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] In particular, it is helpful in investigating problems related to P versus NP.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] For example, if there is any language in NP that is not in P/poly then P $\neq$ NP.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] P/poly also helps to investigate properties of the polynomial hierarchy.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] For example, if NP ⊆ P/poly, then PH collapses to $\Sigma _{2}^{\mathsf {P}}$ .
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A full description of the relations between P/poly and other complexity classes is available at "Importance of P/poly".
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] P/poly also has the interesting feature that it can be equivalently defined as the class of languages recognized by a polynomial-time Turing machine with a polynomial-bounded advice function.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Two subclasses of P/poly that have interesting properties in their own right are NC and AC.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] These classes are defined not only in terms of their circuit size but also in terms of their *depth*.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] The depth of a circuit is the length of the longest directed path from an input node to the output node.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] The class NC is the set of languages that can be solved by circuit families that are restricted not only to having polynomial-size but also to having polylogarithmic depth.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] The class AC is defined similarly to NC, however gates are allowed to have unbounded fan-in (that is, the AND and OR gates can be applied to more than two bits).
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] NC is an important class because it turns out that it represents the class of languages that have efficient parallel algorithms.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] The circuit value problem — the problem of computing the output of a given Boolean circuit on a given input string — is a P-complete decision problem.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Therefore, this problem is considered to be "inherently sequential" in the sense that there is likely no efficient, highly parallel algorithm that solves the problem.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Logic circuits are physical representation of simple logic operations, AND, OR and NOT (and their combinations, such as non-sequential flip-flops or circuit networks), that form a mathematical structure known as Boolean algebra.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] They are complete in sense that they can perform any deterministic algorithm.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] However, it just happens that this is not all there is.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] In the physical world we also encounter randomness, notable in small systems governed by quantization effects, which is described by theory of quantum mechanics.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Logic circuits cannot produce any randomness, and in that sense they form an incomplete logic set.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] Remedy to that is found in adding an ad-hoc random bit generator to logic networks, or computers, such as in probabilistic Turing machine.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] A recent work has introduced a theoretical concept of an inherently random logic circuit named *random flip-flop*, which completes the set.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] It conveniently packs randomness and is inter-operable with deterministic Boolean logic circuits.
[src:nc-class/boolean-circuit] However, an algebraic structure equivalent of Boolean algebra and associated methods of circuit construction and reduction for the extended set is yet unknown.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] In theoretical computer science, **circuit complexity** is a branch of computational complexity theory in which Boolean functions are classified according to the size or depth of the Boolean circuits that compute them.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] A related notion is the circuit complexity of a recursive language that is decided by a **uniform** family of circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ (see below).
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Proving lower bounds on size of Boolean circuits computing explicit Boolean functions is a popular approach to separating complexity classes.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] For example, a prominent circuit class P/poly consists of Boolean functions computable by circuits of polynomial size.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Proving that ${\mathsf {NP}}\not \subseteq {\mathsf {P/poly}}$ would separate P and NP (see below).
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Complexity classes defined in terms of Boolean circuits include AC0, AC, TC0, NC1, NC, and P/poly.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] A Boolean circuit with n input bits is a directed acyclic graph in which every node (usually called *gates* in this context) is either an input node of in-degree 0 labelled by one of the n input bits, an AND gate, an OR gate, or a NOT gate.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] One of these gates is designated as the output gate.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Such a circuit naturally computes a function of its n inputs.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The **size** of a circuit is the number of gates it contains and its **depth** is the maximal length of a path from an input gate to the output gate.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] There are two major notions of circuit complexity.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The **circuit-size complexity** of a Boolean function f is the minimal size of any circuit computing f .
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The **circuit-depth complexity** of a Boolean function f is the minimal depth of any circuit computing f .
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] These notions generalize when one considers the circuit complexity of any formal language that contains strings with different bit lengths, especially infinite languages.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Boolean circuits, however, only allow a fixed number of input bits.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Thus, no single Boolean circuit is capable of deciding such a language.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] To account for this possibility, one considers families of circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ where each $C_{n}$ accepts inputs of size n .
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Each circuit family will naturally generate the language by circuit $C_{n}$ outputting 1 when a length n string is a member of the family, and 0 otherwise.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] We say that a family of circuits is **size minimal** if there is no other family that decides on inputs of any size, n , with a circuit of smaller size than $C_{n}$ (respectively for **depth minimal** families).
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Thus, circuit complexity is meaningful even for non-recursive languages.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The notion of a **uniform family** enables variants of circuit complexity to be related to algorithm-based complexity measures of recursive languages.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] However, the non-uniform variant is helpful to find lower bounds on how complex any circuit family must be in order to decide given languages.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Hence, the **circuit-size complexity** of a formal language A is defined as the function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , that relates a bit length of an input, n , to the circuit-size complexity of a minimal circuit $C_{n}$ that decides whether inputs of that length are in A .
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The **circuit-depth complexity** is defined similarly.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] An individual computational problem is thus associated with a particular *family* of Boolean circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\dots$ where each $C_{n}$ is the circuit handling inputs of *n* bits.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] A *uniformity* condition is often imposed on these families, requiring the existence of some possibly resource-bounded Turing machine that, on input *n*, produces a description of the individual circuit $C_{n}$ .
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] When this Turing machine has a running time polynomial in *n*, the circuit family is said to be P-uniform.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The stricter requirement of DLOGTIME-uniformity is of particular interest in the study of shallow-depth circuit-classes such as AC0 or TC0.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] When no resource bounds are specified, a language is recursive (i.e., decidable by a Turing machine) if and only if the language is decided by a uniform family of Boolean circuits.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Circuit complexity goes back to Shannon in 1949, who proved that almost all Boolean functions on *n* variables require circuits of size Θ(2*n*/*n*).
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Despite this fact, complexity theorists have so far been unable to prove a superlinear lower bound for any explicit function.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Superpolynomial lower bounds have been proved under certain restrictions on the family of circuits used.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The first function for which superpolynomial circuit lower bounds were shown was the parity function, which computes the sum of its input bits modulo 2.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The fact that parity is not contained in AC0 was first established independently by Ajtai in 1983 and by Furst, Saxe and Sipser in 1984.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Later improvements by Håstad in 1987 established that any family of constant-depth circuits computing the parity function requires exponential size.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Extending a result of Razborov, Smolensky in 1987 proved that this is true even if the circuit is augmented with gates computing the sum of its input bits modulo some odd prime *p*.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The *k*-clique problem is to decide whether a given graph on *n* vertices has a clique of size *k*.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] For any particular choice of the constants *n* and *k*, the graph can be encoded in binary using ${n \choose 2}$ bits, which indicate for each possible edge whether it is present.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Then the *k*-clique problem is formalized as a function $f_{k}:\{0,1\}^{n \choose 2}\to \{0,1\}$ such that $f_{k}$ outputs 1 if and only if the graph encoded by the string contains a clique of size *k*.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] This family of functions is monotone and can be computed by a family of circuits, but it has been shown that it cannot be computed by a polynomial-size family of monotone circuits (that is, circuits with AND and OR gates but without negation).
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The original result of Razborov in 1985 was later improved to an exponential-size lower bound by Alon and Boppana in 1987.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] In 2008, Rossman showed that constant-depth circuits with AND, OR, and NOT gates require size $\Omega (n^{k/4})$ to solve the *k*-clique problem even in the average case.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Moreover, there is a circuit of size $n^{k/4+O(1)}$ that computes $f_{k}$ .
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] In 1999, Raz and McKenzie later showed that the monotone NC hierarchy is infinite.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The integer division problem lies in uniform TC0.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Circuit lower bounds are generally difficult.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] It is open whether NEXPTIME has nonuniform TC0 circuits.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Proofs of circuit lower bounds are strongly connected to derandomization.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] A proof that ${\mathsf {P}}={\mathsf {BPP}}$ would imply that either ${\mathsf {NEXP}}\not \subseteq {\mathsf {P/poly}}$ or that the permanent of a matrix cannot be computed by nonuniform arithmetic circuits (polynomials) of polynomial size and polynomial degree.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] In 1997, Razborov and Rudich showed that many known circuit lower bounds for explicit Boolean functions imply the existence of so called natural properties useful against the respective circuit class.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] On the other hand, natural properties useful against P/poly would break strong pseudorandom generators.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] This is often interpreted as a "natural proofs" barrier for proving strong circuit lower bounds.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] In 2016, Carmosino, Impagliazzo, Kabanets and Kolokolova proved that natural properties can be also used to construct efficient learning algorithms.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Many circuit complexity classes are defined in terms of class hierarchies.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] For each non-negative integer *i*, there is a class NCi, consisting of polynomial-size circuits of depth $O(\log ^{i}(n))$ , using bounded fan-in AND, OR, and NOT gates.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] The union NC of all of these classes is a subject of study.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] By considering unbounded fan-in gates, the classes ACi and AC (which is equal to NC) can be constructed.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] Many other circuit complexity classes with the same size and depth restrictions can be constructed by allowing different sets of gates.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] If a certain language, A , belongs to the time-complexity class ${\text{TIME}}(t(n))$ for some function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , then A has circuit complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(t(n)\log t(n))$ .
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] If the Turing Machine that accepts the language is oblivious (meaning that it reads and writes the same memory cells regardless of input), then A has circuit complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(t(n))$ .
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] A monotone Boolean circuit is one that has only AND and OR gates, but no NOT gates.
[src:nc-class/circuit-complexity] A monotone circuit can only compute a monotone Boolean function, which is a function $f:\{0,1\}^{n}\to \{0,1\}$ where for every $x,y\in \{0,1\}^{n}$ , $x\leq y\implies f(x)\leq f(y)$ , where $x\leq y$ means that $x_{i}\leq y_{i}$ for all $i\in \{1,\ldots ,n\}$ .
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] In computational complexity theory, the class **NC** (for "Nick's Class") is the set of decision problems decidable in polylogarithmic time on a parallel computer with a polynomial number of processors.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] In other words, a problem with input size *n* is in **NC** if there exist constants *c* and *k* such that it can be solved in time *O*((log *n*)*c*) using *O*(*n**k*) parallel processors.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Stephen Cook coined the name "Nick's class" after Nick Pippenger, who had done extensive research on circuits with polylogarithmic depth and polynomial size.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] As in the case of circuit complexity theory, usually the class has an extra constraint that the circuit family must be *uniform* (see below).
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Just as the class **P** can be thought of as the tractable problems (Cobham's thesis), so **NC** can be thought of as the problems that can be efficiently solved on a parallel computer.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] **NC** is a subset of **P** because polylogarithmic parallel computations can be simulated by polynomial-time sequential ones.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] It is unknown whether **NC** = **P**, but most researchers suspect this to be false, meaning that there are probably some tractable problems that are "inherently sequential" and cannot significantly be sped up by using parallelism.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Just as the class **NP-complete** can be thought of as "probably intractable", so the class **P-complete**, when using **NC** reductions, can be thought of as "probably not parallelizable" or "probably inherently sequential".
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The parallel computer in the definition can be assumed to be a *parallel, random-access machine* (PRAM).
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] That is a parallel computer with a central pool of memory, and any processor can access any bit of memory in constant time.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The definition of **NC** is not affected by the choice of how the PRAM handles simultaneous access to a single bit by more than one processor.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] See PRAM for descriptions of those models.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] As with **P**, by a slight abuse of language, one might classify function problems and search problems as being in **NC**.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Often algorithms for those problems had to be separately invented and could not be naïvely adapted from well-known algorithms – Gaussian elimination and Euclidean algorithm rely on operations performed in sequence.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] One might contrast ripple carry adder with a carry-lookahead adder.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] An example of problem in NC1 is the parity check on a bit string.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The problem consists in counting the number of 1s in a string made of 1 and 0.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] A simple solution consists in summing all the string's bits.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The smallest class, **NC***0*, is the class of functions definable by Boolean circuits with constant depth and bounded fan-in.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The next-smallest class, **NC***1*, is equal to **BW**4*0* , the set of all problems solvable by polynomial-size, bounded fan-in circuits of width 4 or less.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] This is true for both the uniform and nonuniform case (DLOGTIME-uniformity suffices).
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The NC classes are related to the AC classes, which are defined similarly, but with gates having unbounded fan-in.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] As an immediate consequence of this, **NC** = **AC**.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Similarly, **NC** is equivalent to the problems solvable on an alternating Turing machine restricted to at most two options at each step with *O*(log *n*) space and $(\log n)^{O(1)}$ alternations.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] It is a major open question whether ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}\subsetneq {\mathsf {NC}}^{1}$ (Vollmer 1998, p.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] There are various levels of uniformity being considered.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] A family of Boolean circuits is uniform if the schematics for any member of the family can be produced by a Turing machine under various resource constraints.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] With different levels of constraints, we would obtain possibly different complexity classes, with a more stringent constraint leading to a possibly smaller complexity class.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] By default, the literature uses **LOGSPACE** uniformity.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Because it is possible that ${\mathsf {NC}}^{1}\subsetneq {\mathsf {LOGSPACE}}$ , researchers may use **NC***1*-uniformity, since it is a possible strengthening.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] To avoid self-reference, **NC***1*-uniform **NC***1* is defined as follows: A **NC***1* Boolean circuit family is **NC***1*-uniform if the set of descriptions is decided by an **ALOGTIME** alternating Turing machine.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The machine reads in a length- n description of a Boolean circuit, and halts in time $O(\log n)$ .
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] For higher classes **NC***2*, **NC***3*, ..., there are similar uniformities definable.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] However, for $k\geq 2$ , **NC***k*-uniform **NC***k* and **LOGSPACE**-uniform **NC***k* are equal, and both are equivalent to the following definition: The family is decided by an alternating Turing machine.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The machine reads in a length- n description of a Boolean circuit, and halts in time $O((\log n)^{k})$ and space $O(\log n)$ .
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] One major open question in complexity theory is whether or not every containment in the **NC** hierarchy is proper.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] implies that the entire **NC** hierarchy "collapses" down to some level *i*.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] It is widely believed that (1) is the case, although no proof as to the truth of either statement has yet been discovered.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] If there exists a problem that is **NC**-complete under **LOGSPACE** or **NC***1* reductions, then the **NC** hierarchy collapses.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] A **branching program** with *n* variables of width *k* and length *m* consists of a sequence of *m* instructions.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Each of the instructions is a tuple (*i*, *p*, *q*) where *i* is the index of variable to check (1 ≤ *i* ≤ *n*), and *p* and *q* are functions from {1, 2, ..., *k*} to {1, 2, ..., *k*}.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Numbers 1, 2, ..., *k* are called states of the branching program.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The program initially starts in state 1, and each instruction (*i*, *p*, *q*) changes the state from *x* to *p*(*x*) or *q*(*x*), depending on whether the *i*th variable is 0 or 1.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The function mapping an input to a final state of the program is called the *yield* of the program (more precisely, the yield on an input is the function mapping any initial state to the corresponding final state).
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The program *accepts* a set $A\subseteq 2^{n}$ of variable values when there is some set of functions $F\subseteq k^{k}$ such that a variable sequence $x\in 2^{n}$ is in *A* precisely when its yield is in *F*.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] A family of branching programs consists of a branching program with *n* variables for each *n*.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] It accepts a language when the *n* variable program accepts the language restricted to length *n* inputs.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] It is easy to show that every language *L* on {0,1} can be recognized by a family of branching programs of width 5 and exponential length, or by a family of exponential width and linear length.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Every regular language on {0,1} can be recognized by a family of branching programs of constant width and linear number of instructions (since a DFA can be converted to a branching program).
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] **BWBP** denotes the class of languages recognizable by a family of branching programs of bounded width and polynomial length.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] For instance, it implies that the majority function can be computed by a family of branching programs of constant width and polynomial size, while intuition might suggest that to achieve polynomial size, one needs a linear number of states.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] A branching program of constant width and polynomial size can be easily converted (via divide-and-conquer) to a circuit in **NC**1.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Conversely, suppose a circuit in **NC**1 is given.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Without loss of generality, assume it uses only AND and NOT gates.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Call a branching program α-computing a circuit *C* if it works as identity when *C*'s output is 0, and as *α* when *C*'s output is 1.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] As a consequence of Lemma 1 and the fact that all cycles of length 5 are conjugate, for any two 5-cycles *α*, *β*, if there exists a branching program α-computing a circuit *C*, then there exists a branching program β-computing the circuit *C*, of the same length.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] Suppose we have a circuit *C* which takes inputs *x*1,...,*x**n* and assume that for all subcircuits *D* of *C* and 5-cycles α, there exists a branching program α-computing *D*.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] We will show that for all 5-cycles α, there exists a branching program α-computing *C*.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] By assuming the subcircuits have branching programs so that they are *α*-computing for all 5-cycles *α*∈*S*5, we have shown *C* also has this property, as required.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] The size of the branching program is at most 4*d*, where *d* is the depth of the circuit.
[src:nc-class/nc-complexity] If the circuit has logarithmic depth, the branching program has polynomial length.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] In computational complexity theory, a decision problem is **P-complete** (complete for the complexity class **P**) if it is in **P** and every problem in **P** can be reduced to it by an appropriate reduction.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] The notion of **P-complete** decision problems is useful in the analysis of which problems are difficult to parallelize effectively and which problems are difficult to solve in limited space, specifically when stronger notions of reducibility than polytime-reducibility are considered.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] The specific type of reduction used varies and may affect the exact set of problems.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Generically, reductions stricter than polynomial-time reductions are used, since all languages in **P** (except the empty language and the language of all strings) are **P**-complete under polynomial-time reductions.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] If we use **NC** reductions, that is, reductions that can operate in polylogarithmic time on a parallel computer with a polynomial number of processors, then all **P**-complete problems lie outside **NC** and so cannot be effectively parallelized, under the unproven assumption that **NC** ≠ **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] If we use the stronger log-space reduction, this remains true, but additionally we learn that all **P**-complete problems lie outside L under the weaker unproven assumption that **L** ≠ **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] In this latter case the set **P**-complete may be smaller.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] The class **P**, typically taken to consist of all the "tractable" problems for a sequential computer, contains the class **NC**, which consists of those problems that can be efficiently solved on a parallel computer.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] This is because parallel computers can be simulated on a sequential machine.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] In other words, it is not known whether there are any tractable problems that are inherently sequential.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Just as it is widely suspected that **P** does not equal **NP**, so it is widely suspected that **NC** does not equal **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Similarly, the class **L** contains all problems that can be solved by a sequential computer in logarithmic space.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Such machines run in polynomial time because they can only have a polynomial number of different configurations.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] It is suspected that **L** ≠ **P**; that is, that some problems that can be solved in polynomial time also require more than logarithmic space.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Similarly to the use of NP-complete problems to analyze the **P** = **NP** question, the **P**-complete problems, viewed as the "probably not parallelizable" or "probably inherently sequential" problems, serves in a similar manner to study the **NC** = **P** question.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Finding an efficient way to parallelize the solution to some **P**-complete problem would show that **NC** = **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] It can also be thought of as the "problems requiring superlogarithmic space"; a log-space solution to a **P**-complete problem (using the definition based on log-space reductions) would imply **L** = **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] The logic behind this is analogous to the logic that a polynomial-time solution to an **NP**-complete problem would prove **P** = **NP**: if we have a **NC** reduction from any problem in **P** to a problem *A*, and an **NC** solution for *A*, then **NC** = **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Similarly, if we have a log-space reduction from any problem in **P** to a problem *A*, and a log-space solution for *A*, then **L** = **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] There are many different many-one reductions used when defining **P**-completeness, with variable strengths.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] At the lowest level is **NC**1-reduction, then **L**-reduction, then **NC**2-reduction, **NC**3-reduction, and so on.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] For **NC***k*-reduction and **NC**-reduction, uniformity is imposed, because the intention of **P**-completeness theory is to prove upper bounds.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Non-uniformity is useful for proving lower bounds, but for upper bounds, non-uniformity is unsatisfactory, since they are too powerful for this purpose.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] The standard uniformity condition is **L**-uniformity, meaning that the circuit family should be constructable by a Turing machine, such that given $1^{n}$ as input, it outputs a description of the n -th circuit using $O(\log n)$ working tape.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Given two languages $L,L'$ , define $L\leq _{m}^{{\mathsf {NC}}^{k}}L'$ if and only if there exists a **L**-uniform **NC***k* Boolean circuit family that together computes a function $f:\{0,1\}^{*}\to \{0,1\}^{*}$ , such that $x\in L$ if and only if $f(x)\in L'$ .
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Define $L\leq _{m}^{\mathsf {L}}L'$ if and only if there exists a function $f:\{0,1\}^{*}\to \{0,1\}^{*}$ that is implicitly logspace computable, such that $x\in L$ if and only if $f(x)\in L'$ .
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Define a language L in **P** to be **P**-complete relative to **NC***k*-reduction if and only if for any language $L'$ in **P**, $L'\leq _{m}^{{\mathsf {NC}}^{k}}L$ .
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Usually for **P**-completeness, **NC**-reduction is meant by default, though many results in the literature concerning **P**-completeness still holds even under the strongest assumption of **NC**1-reduction.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] The most basic **P**-complete problem under logspace many-one reductions is the following: given a Turing machine M , an input for that machine *x*, and a number *T* (written in unary), $\langle M,x,T\rangle$ does that machine halt on that input within the first *T* steps?
[src:nc-class/p-complete] To reduce an $L\in {\mathsf {P}}$ to this problem, take a Turing Machine $M_{L}$ deciding L in time bounded by the polynomial *p*.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Then for any $x\in L$ , output the encoding of $M_{L}$ , the encoding of *x* itself, and a number of steps $T=p(|x|)$ .
[src:nc-class/p-complete] The machine *M* halts on *x* within $p(|x|)$ steps if and only if *x* is in *L*.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Clearly, if we can parallelize a general simulation of a sequential computer (i.e. the Turing machine simulation of Turing machines), then we will be able to parallelize any program that runs on that computer.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] If this problem is in **NC**, then so is every other problem in **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] If the number of steps is written in binary, the problem is EXPTIME-complete.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] This problem illustrates a common trick in the theory of **P**-completeness.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] We aren't really interested in whether a problem can be solved quickly on a parallel machine.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] We're just interested in whether a parallel machine solves it *much more* quickly than a sequential machine.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Therefore, we have to reword the problem so that the sequential version is in **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] That is why this problem required *T* to be written in unary.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] If a number *T* is written as a binary number (a string of *n* ones and zeros, where *n* = log *T*), then the obvious sequential algorithm can take time 2*n*.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] On the other hand, if *T* is written as a unary number (a string of *n* ones, where *n* = *T*), then it only takes time *n*.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] By writing *T* in unary rather than binary, we have reduced the obvious sequential algorithm from exponential time to linear time.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] That puts the sequential problem in **P**.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Then, it will be in **NC** if and only if it is parallelizable.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Many other problems have been proved to be **P**-complete, and therefore are widely believed to be inherently sequential.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Most of the languages above are **P**-complete under even stronger notions of reduction, such as uniform $AC^{0}$ many-one reductions, DLOGTIME reductions, or polylogarithmic projections.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] In order to prove that a given problem in **P** is **P**-complete, one typically tries to reduce a known **P**-complete problem to the given one.
[src:nc-class/p-complete] Sivakumar, building on work by Ogihara, showed that if there exists a sparse language that is **P**-complete, then **L** = **P**.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] In computer science, a **parallel random-access machine** (**parallel RAM** or **PRAM**) is a shared-memory abstract machine.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] As its name indicates, the PRAM is intended as the parallel-computing analogy to the random-access machine (RAM) (not to be confused with random-access memory).
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] Similar to the way in which the RAM model neglects practical issues, such as access time to cache memory versus main memory, the PRAM model neglects such issues as synchronization and communication, but provides any (problem-size-dependent) number of processors.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] Algorithm cost, for instance, is estimated using two parameters O(time) and O(time × processor_number).
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] Concurrent read concurrent write (CRCW)—multiple processors can read and write.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] A CRCW PRAM is sometimes called a **concurrent random-access machine**.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] Here, E and C stand for 'exclusive' and 'concurrent' respectively.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] Several simplifying assumptions are made while considering the development of algorithms for PRAM.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] Any memory location is uniformly accessible from any processor.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] There is no limit on the amount of shared memory in the system.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] The programs written on these machines are, in general, of type SIMD.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] These kinds of algorithms are useful for understanding the exploitation of concurrency, dividing the original problem into similar sub-problems and solving them in parallel.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] The introduction of the formal 'P-RAM' model in Wyllie's 1979 thesis had the aim of quantifying analysis of parallel algorithms in a way analogous to the Turing Machine.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] The analysis focused on a MIMD model of programming using a CREW model but showed that many variants, including implementing a CRCW model and implementing on an SIMD machine, were possible with only constant overhead.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] However, the test for practical relevance of PRAM (or RAM) algorithms depends on whether their cost model provides an effective abstraction of some computer; the structure of that computer can be quite different than the abstract model.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] The knowledge of the layers of software and hardware that need to be inserted is beyond the scope of this article.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] The article Ghanim, Vishkin & Barua (2018) demonstrated that PRAM algorithms as-is can achieve competitive performance even without any additional effort to cast them as multi-threaded programs on XMT.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] This is an example of SystemVerilog code which finds the maximum value in the array in only 2 clock cycles.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] It compares all the combinations of the elements in the array at the first clock, and merges the result at the second clock.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] It uses CRCW memory; `m[i] <= 1` and `maxNo <= data[i]` are written concurrently.
[src:nc-class/parallel-ram] The concurrency causes no conflicts because the algorithm guarantees that the same value is written to the same memory.
